Defines the plain-data configuration struct passed to bwrap's command-line builder, plus every cage-internal path constant used to lay out the sandbox filesystem.

`BwrapConfig` has no methods — it's a value collected elsewhere (the bwrap command-builder module) and consumed to produce the actual `bwrap` argv. Fields are documented individually and each carries a specific rationale that matters if touched: `mask_file` must be an empty regular file, not `/dev/null`, because bwrap binds are `nodev` and a masked device node returns EACCES to readers (this broke git on `.git/config`); `target_root` is bound at its identical host path with no cage-side alias because compiled build artifacts embed absolute paths; `resolv_conf` must be present and non-empty even though the cage is offline, because an absent/empty resolver config makes glibc default to `127.0.0.1:53`, which the cage's netns refuses instantly, and something upstream retries in a loop burning a full core for the session (tracked as ADR-049 — don't remove this bind to "simplify" the offline cage).

The path constants (`CAGE_BIN`, `CAGE_RULES_PATH`, `CAGE_RESOLV_PATH`, `CAGE_RUN_DIR`, `API_SOCK_NAME`, `CAGE_CLAUDE_CONFIG`, `CAGE_CLAUDE_CRED`, `CAGE_LOCAL_CLAUDE`) are the cage-side mount targets; whatever module actually invokes `bwrap` must bind host paths to exactly these strings, and both sides need updating together if any moves. `new_session` defaults to `true` (blocks TIOCSTI injection) but must be set `false` for interactive Claude Code sessions so its TUI renders — a caller building for interactive use has to override the `Default`.